  "chunk_index": 3,
  "summary": "An inspector discusses the suspicious \"ABC\" letter with Poirot and Hastings, suggesting that Mary DeLaur, the niece of the deceased Mrs. Asher, might be able to assist with the investigation. The inspector reveals that Mrs. Asher had a difficult past, having left her husband, Franz Ascher, in 1922 after he pestered her for money.\n\nThe police locate Franz Ascher hiding in a car at a railway siding. A volatile and nervous man, Franz denies killing his wife, claiming his previous threats against her were merely jokes. He provides an alibi, stating he was drinking with friends, including Dick Whillock, at the Seven Stars and the Red Dog. Despite his claims, the superintendent takes Franz into custody as a suspect.\n\nPoirot investigates the crime scene and discovers an ABC train timetable, which lists stations alphabetically, left open on the shop counter. This find suggests a direct connection to the \"ABC\" letter. At the morgue, Dr. Kerr explains that the murder weapon was likely a heavy object, such as a club or sandbag, noting that even a physically weak person could have wielded it. Based on the victim's position, Poirot concludes that she was likely facing a customer when she was attacked, a detail he believes supports Franz's innocence. Following this, Poirot and Hastings travel to Overton to interview Mary DeLaur at a large house near the village.",
